{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503393"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:00:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:00:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2025"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2025"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.13,0.01,0.11,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2025"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2025"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2025"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83803"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1085"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4807"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"8363"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34785"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of migratory joint pain that began in his right ankle, progressed to his left knee, and now involves his right wrist. He reports intermittent low back discomfort, particularly in the morning. He also mentions mild irritation in both eyes and occasional dysuria without discharge. His symptoms began approximately five weeks after recovering from a self-limiting febrile illness with abdominal pain and diarrhoea that lasted four days. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a chef and recently returned from a culinary tour in Southeast Asia two months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. There is mild swelling and tenderness of his left knee and right wrist with restricted range of motion. Schober\u0027s test reveals limited lumbar flexion. Bilateral conjunctival injection is noted without discharge. Skin examination reveals a few small painless erythematous macules on the glans penis. Laboratory investigations reveal a white cell count of 10.2 \u00d7 10^9/L (4.0-11.0), C-reactive protein 28 mg/L (\u0026lt;5), and negative rheumatoid factor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most probable diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psoriatic arthritis","Gonococcal arthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis","Ankylosing spondylitis","Reactive arthritis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ereactive arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is an inflammatory arthritis that typically occurs 1-6 weeks following a genitourinary or gastrointestinal infection. The classic triad includes arthritis, conjunctivitis, and urethritis (formerly known as Reiter\u0027s syndrome). This patient demonstrates all three components: asymmetric oligoarthritis affecting the lower limbs and wrist, conjunctival injection, and urethritis (dysuria). The presence of painless erythematous macules on the glans penis (likely circinate balanitis) and the temporal relationship to a preceding gastrointestinal illness further support this diagnosis. Reactive arthritis is more common in young men, and HLA-B27 positivity increases susceptibility.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonococcal arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with migratory polyarthralgia and tenosynovitis, but typically has a more acute onset with fever and characteristic pustular skin lesions. The absence of urethral discharge and the clear temporal relationship to a gastrointestinal illness rather than a sexually transmitted infection make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with symmetric polyarthritis predominantly affecting the small joints of the hands and feet. The negative rheumatoid factor (though not definitive), the asymmetric joint involvement, the presence of conjunctivitis and urethritis, and the temporal relationship to a preceding infection are inconsistent with rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnkylosing spondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the axial skeleton with chronic inflammatory back pain and progressive spinal stiffness. While this patient has some back discomfort, the predominant peripheral joint involvement and the presence of extra-articular manifestations following a recent infection are more consistent with reactive arthritis. However, it\u0027s worth noting that reactive arthritis and ankylosing spondylitis are both spondyloarthropathies and share some clinical features and association with HLA-B27.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with asymmetric oligoarthritis, but is typically associated with psoriatic skin lesions (silvery scales on erythematous plaques) and nail changes (pitting, onycholysis). The absence of these characteristic skin and nail findings, along with the presence of conjunctivitis, urethritis, and the temporal relationship to a preceding infection, make psoriatic arthritis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reactive arthritis is an inflammatory condition that typically follows genitourinary or enteric infections by 1-6 weeks.","The classic triad of reactive arthritis includes arthritis, conjunctivitis, and urethritis.","HLA-B27 positivity is associated with increased risk of developing reactive arthritis and other spondyloarthropathies."],"references":["Schmitt SK. Reactive arthritis. Infect Dis Clin North Am. 2017 Jun;31(2):265-277. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28292540/","Selmi C, Gershwin ME. Diagnosis and classification of reactive arthritis. Autoimmun Rev. 2014 Apr-May;13(4-5):546-9. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24418301/","Jubber, A., \u0026 Moorthy, A. (2021). Reactive arthritis: a clinical review. Journal of the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh, 51(3), 288-297. Available from: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.4997/jrcpe.2021.319"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83803"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2025"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83803"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T15:03:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T15:04:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2025"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101373"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id"